[[File:The gallows at Central Jail of Nicosia.JPG|thumb|width=200px|right|upright|The gallows at the Nicosia Central Prison, now a museum (2006)]]
[[Capital punishment]] for [[murder]] was abolished in [[Cyprus]] on 15 December 1983. It was abolished for all crimes on 19 April 2002. The death penalty was replaced with [[life imprisonment]]. Cyprus is a signatory of the [[Second Optional Protocol to the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights|second optional protocol]] of the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]] which provides for full abolition of capital punishment. Cyprus initially had a reservation on the second protocol, allowing execution for grave crimes in times of war, but subsequently gave up this reservation.

The last executions were carried out on 13 June 1962. Three men, Hambis Zacharia, Michael Hiletikos and Lazaris Demetriou, were hanged for murder at the [[Central Jail of Nicosia]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.capitalpunishmentuk.org/europe.html |title=The end of capital punishment in Europe |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Capital Punishment U.K. |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref> the country's only prison. Zacharia had killed a man in 1958 in a [[Limassol]] vineyard. Hiletikos and Demetriou were convicted of shooting a man outside a Limassol night-club in 1961. The British executioners [[Harry Allen (executioner)|Harry Allen]] and John Underhill travelled to Cyprus to carry out the hangings.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?series_number=13&id=681 | title=June 13th 13/6/1962 Hambia Zacharia, Michael Hiletikos and Lazaris Demetriou – Cyprus | publisher=True Crime Library | accessdate=12 March 2015 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402142425/http://www.truecrimelibrary.com/crime_series_show.php?series_number=13&id=681 | archivedate=2 April 2015 | df= }}</ref>

Prior to independence, nine men had been hanged in 1956 and 1957 by the British for acts committed as members of [[EOKA]]. The Central Jail of Nicosia still functions as a prison, but the area where executions were carried out is now a museum.

{{anchor|Northern Cyprus}}
The unrecognised state of the [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]] retains the death penalty in limited circumstances. Article 15 of the state's constitution declares that capital punishment can be imposed in cases of treason during wartime, acts of terrorism and [[piracy jure gentium|piracy ''jure gentium'']], and for repeated murders. Even in these instances, no execution of capital punishment can be carried out unless the [[Assembly of the Republic (Northern Cyprus)|Northern Cyprus legislative assembly]] decides so under the provisions of Article 78. {{As of|2017}}, Northern Cyprus has never carried out an execution.

